ges in parental provisioning rates of nestling birds associated with predation risk ( Ghalambor et al. 2013 ), and nest-site selection in a turtle,   Chrysemys picta   ( Refsnider and Janzen 2012 ).  Birds use a variety of methods to help alter and maintain nest microclimate, which provides evidence for the importance of incubation temperature to the proper development of embryos ( Deeming 2002 ). Modifying incubation behaviors, as we have shown in Wood Ducks, is one method that affects incubation temperature and has been reported in many species (e.g.,  Martin et al. 2007 ). Nest size and structure can improve the thermal characteristics of nests ( Rohwer and Law 2010 ,  Mainwaring et al. 2012 ,  Heenan 2013 ), thereby helping to slow egg cooling rates ( Hilton et al. 2004 ,  Windsor et al. 2013 ). Selection of nest sites also can affect nest microclimate by influencing exposure to environmental conditions ( Nelson and Martin 1999 ,  Ardia et al. 2006 ). Further, parents at temperate latitudes can mediate the costs of incubation and help maintain optimal nest temperatures by simply nesting later in the season, when ambient temperatures are warmer ( Hepp and Kennamer 2011 ).  Recent studies have shown that Wood Duck eggs incubated at low temperatures developed more slowly and that embryos used more energy and hatched with fewer residual lipids ( Hepp et al. 2006 ,  DuRant et al. 2011 ,  Hepp and Kennamer 2012 ). These ducklings also had poor locomotor skills, reduced growth rates, reduced levels of immunocompetence, increased stress levels, and increased costs of thermoregulation compared with ducklings incubated at higher temperatures ( DuRant et al. 2010 ,  2011 ,  2012a ,  2012b ,  Hopkins et al. 2011 ). Further,  Hepp and Kennamer (2012)  showed that ducklings incubated at low temperatures were less likely to survive and reproduce than ducklings incubated at higher temperatures. Negative impacts of low incubation temperature also have been reported for other birds. For example, low incubation temperature negatively influenced the subsequent growth and metabolism of Blue Tits (  Cyanistes caeruleus  ;  Nord and Nilsson 2011 ) and the growth and innate immune function of Tree Swallows ( Ardia et al. 2010 ). However, effects of these phenotypic differences on fitness are still relatively unexplored.  It is clear that proper care of eggs is important for optimal reproductive success in birds, but incubation constancy and incubation temperature often vary within and between species ( Hepp et al. 2006 ,  Hepp and Kennamer 2011 ,  Martin et al. 2013 ). Incubation is costly for parents, and these costs increase with decreasing ambient temperature and increasing clutch size ( Reid et al. 2002 ,  Tinbergen and Williams 2002 ,  Nord et al. 2010 ). Parents that were energetically constrained often invested more in self-maintenance and spent less time on the nest ( Ardia et al. 2009 ,  MacDonald et al. 2013 ). However, tradeoffs can be mediated by parental quality ( Hanssen et al. 2003 ). In Wood Ducks, heavy females that were in good condition nested earlier, spent more time incubating, and lost more weight than females in poor condition that nested later in the season, when ambient temperatures were warmer ( Hepp and Kennamer 2011 ).  In the present study, female Wood Ducks did not appear to be energetically constrained. For example, they began incubation in better body condition than females from an earlier study of this population (567 vs. 543 g;  Hepp and Kennamer 2011 ) and lost &lt;3&percnt; of their body mass during incubation. As incubation costs increased with declining ambient temperature and greater clutch cooling rates, females spent more time on nests to keep eggs warm rather than investing in self-maintenance. These behavioral changes kept eggs at optimal developmental temperatures without negatively affecting female body condition. However, if environmental conditions had been more severe (i.e. colder temperatures or reduced habitat quality), we would have expected females, especially those starting incubation in relatively poor condition, to have reduced incubation effort and sacrificed clutch temperatures for self-maintenance. Modifying strategies and investing more in self-maintenance makes sense when females are energetically constrained, because finishing incubation at low body mass can reduce female survival ( Hepp et al. 1990 ).  We found that female Wood Ducks generally managed incubation costs successfully. Females were sensitive to changes in both ambient temperature and cooling rate of clutches and modified incubation behaviors to successfully maintain an optimal nest microclimate without affecting their body condition. The ability of females to make these changes and provide embryos with an optimal thermal environment ultimately depends on individual quality and prevailing environmental conditions. Incubation is an important reproductive cost, and successfully negotiating this cost can affect neonate quality as well as the survival and future reproduction of parents. In the future, how anticipated changes in climate and habitat quality influence tradeoffs between parents and offspring during this important period of reproduction in birds will be important areas of investigation.  Thanks are due to our field crew, J. McPherson, N. Allen, C. Weithman, and C. Gesmundo. We also thank T. Steury for statistical assistance, and the staff at the Savannah River Ecology Lab for support and hospitality. The Institutional Animal Care and Use Committee of Auburn University approved our research (PRN 2010-1691). Ducklings were collected under permits issued by the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service (MB 748024-0) and South Carolina (G-10-02). Research was supported by National Science Foundation grant IOB-0615361 to G.R.H., the Alabama Agricultural Experiment Station, and the Department of Energy under award DE-FC09-07SR22506 to the University of Georgia Research Foundation. 